The XRD, UV–Visible, FTIR and Raman spectrum of the synthesized CQDs are displayed in Fig. 2
                        (a–d). The XRD of prepared CQDs is showed in Fig. 2(a), which is demonstrated the peak position at 2θ angles 22.52° with (002) lattice plane is well confirmed that the as-prepared CQDs is amorphous graphite, is due to the addition of N- and O-containing groups. These findings are consistent with those previously published for CQDs [44]. These findings suggest that the carbon source in SB was successfully extracted and converted into CQDs. The physical characteristics of CQDs extracted from waste materials were determined using UV–Visible spectroscopy. The UV–Visible spectroscopy of synthesized CQDs is displayed in Fig. 2(b). The UV spectrum of CQDs revealed two distinct peaks at 242 and 310 nm, which are found in SB. A characteristic absorption peak at 242 nm was allocated to the л–л* transition of graphitic aromatic sp2 domains (CC), and yet another n–л* absorption band at 310 nm (CO) was also detected [45]. The water solution of CQDs is yellow and colourless in visible light, but when exposed to UV light in the long UV (365 nm) range, it transforms into an extreme sky blue luminescent solution (insets Fig. 2b). The CQDs water solution remained relatively stable without precipitation for a long time. FTIR (Fourier transforms infrared) spectroscopy is a simple, rapid, and non-destructive technique. The surface composition of the obtained CQDs was also analyzed using FTIR spectrum is displayed in Fig. 2(c). The evaluation demonstrated the existence of OH and CH functional groups in all fractions, with usual peaks observed around 3423 and 2782 cm−1, respectively. The absorption peaks at 1633 cm−1 is allocated to CO stretching vibrations [46,47]. It should be remembered that the sharpest peak for all fractions corresponding to the CC group was 1510 cm−1, illustrating the graphitic existence of the CQDs. The absorption peaks in the zone of 1276 cm−1 are linked to the CN stretching vibration, while the peak at 1028 cm−1 is related to the CO stretching vibration [48,49]. Raman spectroscopy is a simple and non-destructive method for characterizing the lattice structure as well as the electronic, optical, and phonon characteristics of carbon materials. Fig. 2(d) displays the Raman spectrum of synthesized CQDs. The D and G bands are indicated by strong peaks in the Raman spectra at 1353 cm−1 and 1595 cm−1, respectively. The Raman spectrum vibration peak at 1353 cm−1 was attributed to the D band, which emerged from the disordered carbon structure, and a graphitic G-band at ∼1595 cm−1 relating to the graphitic domains (sp2 hybridization) in the structure [50,51]. The intensity ratio (ID/IG
                        ) of the disordered D band to the crystalline G band was approximately 0.84, confirming the bagasse-derived CQDs' partial amorphous in nature. The structure of the CQDs is comparable to graphene oxide, as revealed by the Raman spectra. The simple demonstration of the high extreme peak of G–band presence of (sp2 carbon), and the low-intensity peak of D–band proving the amorphous (few oxygen functional groups) defects and disorder present in the CQDs.
